column168: On 04/04/14, railcar TILX 191876 arrived at the facility. One of the employees inspected the railcar and found a 2 inch plug not installed on the railcar and evidence of product released on the sides of the railcar during transit. It is estimated about one gallon of crude oil was on the side of the railcar. The shipper was notified and was going to investigate. The plug was reinstalled and the railcar was emptied.
column169: Continue to report any issues to the shipper in an effort to eliminate any future issues.

column168: Our driver picked up a 20 cy box at the shipper business and delivered it the consignee.  At the our driver arrived at the consignee they were closed; the driver dropped the box on the 10-day drop yard for delivery when the receiver opened for business.  The receiver went to pick the box up to unload and noticed a small leak from the back of the box door.  The leak was stopped the box off-loaded and the area cleaned of any spilled material.  The material in the box is manifested as Waste Corrosive Liquid, Acidic, inorganic, 8, III,(d002),(d007).  The waste profile verifies inerts as sulfate residuals and sulfuric acid sludge  100%, debris (metal, brick, ceramic packing  Max 49% and Chromium 316 MG/L TC.  Our company does not believe the amount of spilled material requires a report but since Chromium is listed with the profile we felt a report would not be ill received. The total content of the chromium was .003 lbs but the company wants to be sure all compliance levels are met.
column169: The company has spoken with the driver and has reiterated the need to be diligent in verification of all seals, gaskets and other possible areas for leaking when transporting and dropping roll-off containers.  We have instituted a progressive disciplinary action for dropping of boxes and other style containers that are loaded with waste.  The driver will receive a written warning for this event.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: A release of 96% sulfuric acid occurred from a pipeline.  This pipeline was being used to transfer material from one tank at the plant to a second tank at our dock facility.  The second tank was loading a barge on a separate pipeline that was not involved in the leak.  The failure was due to internal erosion/corrosion which created a 1/4" hole.  Material was released to the ground with no impact to water or sewer systems.  Material released was 96% sulfuric acid.  Total quantity was 68.6 gallons or 1052 pounds.  On a 100% basis would equal 1010 pounds.  Release was stopped by turning off a transfer pump.  Impacted soils were excavated and placed into containers for proper disposal.  Failed section of pipe was replaced.  Pipeline was pressure tested and put back into service.
column169: Further NDT testing of similar pipes.  Replace similar sections in our fresh acid pipeline.

HAZMAT totes were being loaded on a 53 ft. van. Plywood was placed around the first 2 totes loaded to proctect them. The trailer was sitting approximately 4 inches below the dock, and the tandems of the trailer were slid all the way back. When going in with the final tote it was placed on the floor, and the then forklift was backed out of the tote. The weight of the first 2 totes loaded caused the trailer to drop even further. The forklift was driven back into the trailer to slide the tote up against the left side of the trailer. When going into the trailer the forklift slid on a piece of plywood that was on the floor causing the forks to puncture the tote. A combination of the trailer sitting so low and the plywood caused the forklift to slide. Almost all of  the tote was released and spilled into our yard, but did not go into any drainage. A barrier was set up using quick dry to contain the area of the spill. Our safety department was called and a team sent in to clean the spill.

column168: The Veolia stopped while in-transit for the employees to take a lunch break. Upon exiting the vehicle and performing the walk around of the truck, the Veolia employees saw a couple of drips of a red material from the truck cargo area. Upon further investigation it was discovered that 1 of the 16 drums of Waste printing ink had a hole on the bottom of the drum. The drum was overpacked on the truck by DOT trained Veolia employees and the small amount of printing ink that had dripped onto the paved parking lot of the address was cleaned up with speedi dri absorbant and placed into the overpack with the leaking drum. The Veolia truck floor was wiped down to absorb any ink that was present on the floor and these wipes were also placed into the overpacked drum for disposal.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. arrived at the Kent, WA facility for transfer of waste to its final disposal facility. National Response Center report# 1079111.
column169: All material handlers at the facility involved in the incident have been counseled and received retraining on properly palletizing, staging, and loading / unloading drummed waste. They have been instructed on always being aware and attentive to their surroundings while operating drum dollies and forklifts in the process of handling drummed waste.  Additionally, they have been instructed to double check that drums are properly and fully placed onto drum dollies, drum grabbers, or pallets prior to attempting to load and or move them.

column168: A tanker loaded with hazardous waste arrived at the intended waste disposal facility.  During the routine check in facility, it was noticed that the tanker appeared to be leaking from the dome.  The driver realized that the ball valve connected to the pressure relief valve was in the open position.  A response crew was summoned, cleaned up the spilled material from the side of the tanker and closed the valve properly.  The tanker was then admitted into the intended waste disposal facility without further incident.
column169: The driver was issued a written warning and re-trained on properly closing all valves after loading.  This was also the topic of a safety meeting with all drivers--the importance of thoroughly checking that all valves are closed prior to departing a stop.

column168: A van trailer containing hazardous arrived at the Clean Harbors Bristol CT facility in order to transfer and consolidate its waste on a van trailer to its intended waste disposal facility. Bristol facility personell noticed that there was a leaking cubic yard box container. A response crew donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and unloaded the leaking cubic yard box; the cubic yard box was repacked for continued transportation. The box trucks floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service. Clean Harbors notified the Bristol Fire Department and the CT DEP of the spill shortly after clean up.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or breakage was observed. It is believed that liquid leached out of the waste in the  cubic yard box and the liner failed not withstanding the rigors of transport. The shipper was notified and advised to use a more appropriate UN rated container for future shipment of this waste stream.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Valve Stem
column168: On April 2, 2014 at 05:10 hours, Car Inspectors at the CSXT Frontier Yard discovered GBRX 700430, UN 1267, a loaded petroleum crude oil car, with oil residue and wetness on the sides of the tank car. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Eighty-Eight Oil, LLC was notified, CHEMTREC Report 2014-04-02-00043. EP+S of Vermont, Buffalo Office, a CSX Emergency Response Contractor was dispatched to the yard, upon inspection, GBRX 700430 was found to product seeping around closed liquid line valve stem packing, packing gland nut was loose hanging on valve stem shaft and the secondary securement plug that was less than tool tight. column168: On 04/08/2014 at approximately 15:00 personnel working on CSXT mainline discovered CTCX 732143 leaking on passing train. CSXT workers radioed train crew who brought the train to a safe stop. It was discovered that CTCX 732143 , a loaded tank car of Alcohols NOS had been leaking from top of the car. The shipper Flint Hills Resources 316-828-2749, local, state and/or federal agencies as applicable were notified CHEMTREC Report # 2014 0408 00189. SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the vapor valve was less than tool tight on the threaded nipple with the operating handle bent to fit under the bread box. column168: A LOADER IN THE UPS SYRACUSE HUB NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM A PACKAGE.  HE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED HIS MANAGEMENT WHO IN TURN SUMMONED A UPS DESIGNATED RESPONDER.  THE RESPONDER SET THE PARCEL OUTSIDE THE BUILDING AND OPENED IT, FINDING A NUMBER OF FOIL PACKETS INSIDE.  ONE OF THE FOIL PACKETS, WHICH HAD TURNED BLACK, BURST INTO FLAMES AND WAS EXTINGUISHED BY ANOTHER EMPLOYEE WITH A FIRE EXTINGUISHER.  INSPECTION OF THE PACKAGE CONTENTS AFTER THE FIRE REVEALED THAT EACH FOIL PACKET INCLUDED A FLAMMABLE SOLID LABEL AS WELL AS A STATEMENT OF COMPLIANCE WITH 49 CFR 173.4.  THE OUTER FIBERBOARD CARTON DISPLAYED THE EXCEPTED QUANTITIES MARKING FROM 173.4A.  THIS MARKING DISPLAYED THE DIVISION NUMBER (4.1) AS WELL AS THE NUMBER 35.  WHEN CONTACTED, THE SHIPPER EXPLAINED THE MATERIAL IS A PYROTECHNIC INITIATOR MADE OF REACTIVE METALS, CLASSIFIED AS UN3178.  WHEN ASKED FOR REPORTS ON PACKAGE TESTING IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE REQUIREMENT OF 173.4 OR 174.4A, THE SHIPPER AS UNABLE TO FURNISH THEM AT THE TIME.

A Clean Harbors Environmental Services vehicle was in the process of loading a hazardous waste load at a client's facility. During the course of loading one of the 55 gallon poly drums was discovered to be leaking its contents from the drum bung/bung hole. Facility personnel donned the proper PPE and contained and cleaned the release. The remaining 4 drums of the shipment were rejected for transportation and the client agreed to repackage them into more physically sound containers to be shipped at a later date. The Washington Department of Ecology was notified of the incident.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. The driver, however, was re-instructed to conduct a thorough inspection of each container before acceptance and if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity is found to take appropriate action to place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re containerize before loading and transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the incident and was requested to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect integrity.

column168: A FRA Hazardous Material Inspector in the railyard observed tank car PROX 44889 with fresh commodity on its side shell. Further inspection of PROX 44889 by the Inspector revealed its 4 inch liquid valve's closure plug was not tool tight, but hand tight only which allowed commodity to escape at this valve's port closure. The liquid valve was reported in the closed position by the Inspector. A BNSF mechanical responder properly tool tightened the liquid valve's closure plug ending any further commodity release from the liquid valve's port closure orifice. Non-evaporated spillage was wiped and no ground impact from the spillage was reported.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column58: Manway or Dome Cover; Vacuum Relief Valve
column62: Defective Component or Device; Misaligned Material, Component, or Device
column168: Residue tank car UTLX 68502 was reported emanating an odor while in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspecting UTLX 68502 reported the odor source was at the manway closure with no liquid commodity observed around the base of the manway nozzle. Further inspection revealed that the vacuum relief valve (VRV) installed in the manway lid was stuck in an open position due to the pressure seal (o-ring) slightly out of position. The pressure seal was adjusted and the VRV reseated itself. Also, the applied manway lid gasket was pinched and a new manway gasket was installed. The manway was closed, secured and sealed. Afterwards, the commodity odor dissipated. UTLX 68502 was released to proceed to its destination.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car GAMX 6529 was reported with a small amount of commodity spillage on its side shell and emanating odor/vapors while in the railyard. Inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder revealed that the applied manway nozzle gasket was torn/shredded and not sealing which allowed commodity to escape at the manway closure. A new manway nozzle gasket was installed and the manway closure was secured and sealed. Non-evaporated spillage was wiped.  GAMX 6529's side specification stencil indicated that its last tank qualification was completed in the year 2004.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A BNSF inbound train inspection in the railyard revealed tank car TCLX 318030 leaking commodity from its top fitting area. A Safety Kleen Systems Inc. material handler was in the process of loading palletized drums of hazardous waste at an accumulation site for transportation to its final disposal destination. In the process of moving a pallet of drums with a forklift one of the drums tipped off of the pallet and fell onto its side bending the chime causing approximately 10 gallons of material to be released from the drum. Facility personnel donned the proper PPE and cleaned the released material. The damaged drum was repackaged into a salvage drum with the associated clean up materials and transported to the disposal destination. The Minnesota Pollution Control Agency - Hazardous Waste Division was notified. Duty officer #33 issued report  #141066.
column169: All material handlers at the facility involved in the incident have been counseled and received retraining on properly palletizing, staging, and loading drummed waste. They have been instructed on always being aware and attentive to their surroundings while operating drum dollies and forklifts in the process of handling drummed waste. Additionally, they have been instructed to double check that drums are properly and fully placed onto the pallet prior to attempting to load and or move them.

column168: On April 18, 2014 at 12:00 hours personnel in the CSXT Howell Yard discovered GATX 7541, a loaded tank car of Sulfuric Acid leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Mosaic Fertilizer LLC, was notified CHEMTREC Report #2014-0418-00140.  Joseph McCann, a CSXT hazardous materials manager, was dispatched to the scene and found that the fill hole cover bolts were less than tool tight. While performing switching operations product released from the car landed on employee's arm causing a burning sensation. Employee was treated for first degree burns on his left forearm at a local hospital and released.  The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shippers representative Melody Russo 575-499-8349.  The release was secured, however, due to other exceptions that were not NAR contributors that were noted upon inspection the tank car was held in the terminal pending additional repairs.  Once the necessary repairs are performed the car will be released for transportation.     NARRI: 5(5+3+0) x (2+7) = 360  Cause Code: 224

column58: Frangible Disc; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: At 06:00 hours on April 8, 2014, Axial Industries (Axial) reported a possible hazmat release in the Rosebluff yard (which is adjacent to the Axial facility).  Proper notifications were made by all involved.  Axial responded to the report and discovered AXLX 988, a loaded chlorine car, to be leaking. The point of release was the Pressure Relief Device (PRD). Axial responders installed a C-Kit (capping kit) onto the PRD securing the release. The Louisiana State Police hazmat responders inspected the capping kit and approved its installation. The protective housing cover was secured for movement. This car was subsequently moved into the Axial facility to be unloaded under 49CFR174.50. As information, this car was released by Axial (April 1, 2014) as an overload. The car was detected overloaded and was being moved back into the shipper facility. It is suspected that the overload caused the premature failure of the PRD.    File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.      (Please direct your root cause investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: On April 22, 2014 CSX was notified by DuPont that PLCX 224660 was requested to be set out at Buffalo, NY, and that PLCX 224660 a residue UN2735, last containing AMINES, Liquid Corrosive, N.O.S was to be inspected for a suspect leak point from the BOV, on April 24, 2014. RESCAR, Inc. a mobile response tank car contractor was dispatched to inspect the tank car. RESCAR found a release point between the Tank Car Shell and the Bottom Outlet Valve housing, a suspect gasket problem as there was wetness on the BOV housing. At 15:05 hours RESCAR and DuPont reported the NAR to CSX, RESCAR checked the torque on the mounting hex-head bolts, no exception. CSX Hazardous Materials Systems dispatched a contractor, EP+S of Vermont to contain and remove any residual product from the tank car, then clean + purge the tank car for safety concerns. April 25, 2014 the PLCX 224660 was cleaned + purged, and certificate of the process was issued. DuPont submitted an OTMA-3 for Home Shop Disposition.    Cause Code: 544  NARRI: 2x(1+7+0)x(2+0) = 32    This DID require a special switch move.

column168: Upon making a delivery, the driver failed to properly secure his drum cart.  Subsequently, while in transit, the drum cart came loose and slid across the trailer floor striking the side of the subject container with a sharp point, rendering a gash in the drum approximately 5" up the side, releasing most of its contents onto the trailer floor.  The driver stopped for fuel, and upon doing so, noticed liquid leaking from the trailer and upon investigation found the release.  Driver acted to contain the spilled liquid with containers, tarps and absorbants.  Driver notified carrier of the release and an emergency response contractor was elicited to help.  Contractor arrived on scene, secured the release and cleaned up the spilled material.  All resulting wastes were containerized and disposed of at an appropriate facility.  Fire department investigated and did not find any material released to the roadway outside fuel depot.
column169: Recommended improvements to methods to secure equipment within trailers, in addition to lading.

column168: After arrival on an inbound BNSF train in the railyard, entrained tank car TILX 220056 was observed with commodity on its side shell. Also observed was entrained tank car NATX 250146 directly trailing TILX 220056 with commodity spray from TILX 220056. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders inspecting TILX 220056 reported finding loose bolts on the flange connection of the valve pressure plate fitting or the protective housing nozzle flange connection. These loose stud bolts were tool tightened. The spillage pattern indicated that this unsecured flange connection was the primary leak source.  Afterwards, both TILX 220056 and NATX 250146 were moved and isolated in the railyard for cleaning of the commodity spillage and spray on their tank shells. This cleaning was accomplished on 4/18/2014. Earmarked for appropriate disposal was all rinsate that was captured, along with other spent cleaning materials. The response contractor tasked to clean the commodity spillage from these two tank cars also inspected the securement integrity of all other valves and fittings on TILX 220056. The contractor reported finding all four mounting flange bolt nuts loose on the liquid valve's flange connection and these were tool tightened. This loose flange connection was likely a secondary leak source. Pressurized nitrogen was inserted into TILX 220056 to verify that no further leak sources existed.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemeneted and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: ON FRIDAY, APRIL 4, 2014 AT APPROXIMATELY 0410 HOURS A SPILL WAS DISCOVERED AT THE KOCH NITROGEN COMPANY, LLC (KNC) WOLSEY TERMINAL. THE SPILL OCCURRED WHEN KNC'S CONTRACTOR, BLICK'S PHOSPHATE CONVERSIONS, LLC (BLICK'S) WAS BUBBLING PHOSPHORIC ACID WITH AIR INSIDE A RAILCAR.  KNC HAS CONTACTED WIT BLICK'S TO OPERATE THE BLICK'S PORTABLE REACTOR TO PRODUCE AMMONIUM POLYPHOSPHATE FERTILIZER (APP) AT KNC'S TERMINAL LOCATED IN RAILCARS.    THE BLICK'S OPERATORS WERE UNAWARE THAT THE FITTING CHOSEN ON THE TOP OF THE RAILCAR THAT THEY BELIEVED TO BE A VENT WAS A DIP-TUBE.  WITH THE DIP-TUBE OPENED (RATHER THAN THE INTENDED VENT), DURING THE AIR BUBBLING PRESSURE BUILT UP IN THE RAILCAR FORCING LIQUID FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE RAILCAR OUT OF THE TOP OF THE DIP-TUBE.    DURING THE BUBBLING, THE BLICK'S OPERATOR ON DUTY INSPECTS THE EQUIPMENT PERIODICALLY.  DURING HIS INSPECTION AT APPROXIMATELY 0410 HOURS, THE OPERATOR DISCOVERED SPILL ON THE GROUND.  THE BUBBLING WAS TERMINATED AND THE BLICK'S OPERATOR NOTIFIED THE ON-SITE KNC OPERATOR OF THE RELEASE.  KNC MADE NOTIFICATIONS TO THE NRC, SD, DENR, AND BEADLE COUNTY EMD REGARDING THIS INCIDENT.    THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED ON SITE WITH AN EARTHEN BERN.  LIME WAS BROUGHT ONSITE TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID.  THE LIME, ACID AND SOIL WERE MIXED TO ENSURE NEUTRALIZATION.  THE NEUTRALIZED SOIL WAS TAKEN TO THE PIERRE LANDFILL AFTER THE LANDFILL HAD RECIEVED APPROVAL FROM SD DENR.
column169: BLICK'S AND KNC ARE REVIEWING THE POTENTIAL CORRECTIVE ACTIONS FOR THE RELEASE.  BASED ON THIS PRELIMINARY INVESTIGATION, BLICK'S IS MODIFYING THE PROCEDURE TO ONLY VENT THROUGH THE RAILCAR MAN WAY AFTER A RECOMMENDATION BY THE RAILCAR OWNER.  ALSO, ALL REACTING PROCEDURES WILL BE UPDATED TO PERFORM EQUIPMENT INSPECTIONS EVERY 15 MINUTES VERSUS THE CURRENT 30 MINUTE ROUNDS.  THOSE PROCEDURES WILL BE IMPLEMENTED BEFORE PRODUCING APP AT THE WOLSEY TERMINAL.

column168: THIS WAS PART OF A PANNED FLATBED LOAD OF UN-DRAINED TRANSFORMERS FROM IOWA TO U.S. ECOLOGY IN BEATTY, NV. THERE WERE NO PROBLEMS UNTIL JUST BEFORE DELIVERY. THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL PUDDLE IN THE CENTER OF THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN. HE APPLIED ABSORBENT AND MONITORED THE LOAD AS HE WAS ONLY ABOUT AN HOUR AND A HALF FROM HIS DESTINATION WHEN HE NOTICED THE PUDDLE. ONCE HE ARRIVED AT US ECOLOGY HE IMMEDIATELY INFORMED PERSONNEL THERE THAT THERE WAS A LEAK FROM ONE OF THE TRANSFORMERS ON THE LOAD.    THERE WERE APPROXIMATELY 2 TO 3 GALS. OF PCB OIL IN THE PAN AND APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS WERE DRAINED FROM THE TRANSFORMER AT US ECOLOGY. THE CAPACITY FOR THE CONTAINER IS MAXIMUM 30 GALLONS. THE TRAILER WAS QUARANTINED IN THE PCB BUILDING AT US ECOLOGY. REBECCA HOGABOAM OF US ECOLOGY NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER OF A POSSIBLE PCB SPILL. THE TRAILER WAS TESTED FOR CONTAMINATION AND THE SWIPES TESTED LESS THAN 50 PPM FOR PCB CONTAMINATION. THE WOODEN NAILER STRIPS WERE REMOVED, BUT THE TRAILER WAS WIPED DOWN AND POWER WASHED THEN RELEASED WITH AUTHORIZATION FROM EPA.
column169: TRANSFORMERS CONTAINING PCB'S SHOULD BE TRAINED AND PACKED W/ ABSORBANT PRIOR TO SHIPMENT.

column168: Our driver was exiting our Liquid CO2 plant after loading and heading out to our customer in Whitehall, AR. Our drivers have to cross a rail spur that comes into our plant and then the main line track on the county road that takes the trucks over to the traffic light on US 49. Our driver states that he did not hear the train whistle nor could he see the train approaching because of the curve in the railroad tracks until he had started to cross the track. Our driver said that he tried to get across the track but did not make it and was struck by the train in the rear of the trailer just in front of the trailer wheels. The impact from the train caused the trailer to be turned over on its side and drug down the tracks about 100 feet along with the tractor which remained upright. None of the valves failed as all were shut off and the tank did not rupture or crack but because the tank was laying on its side the liquid CO2 was coming out of the vapor relief valve and changing to vapor as soon as it hit atmoshere. Until a couple of wreckers could come and upright the trailer and get the liquid CO2 away from the vapor safety it continued to vent to atmoshere.
column169: Rankin County--the traffic control sign at the corner of Andrew Jackson Circle & Dixie Rd was changed from a Stop to a Yield sign. We developed a SOP for safely crossing the tracks and trained all drivers. column168: Tank car NATX 231217 was reported leaking commodity from its manway closure while in the railyard. Contract responders inspecting NATX 231217 reported finding 4 of 8 manway securement bolt/nuts not tool tight. The manway gasket was inspected and found serviceable. The responders closed and secured the manway cover by properly tool tightening all the manway securement bolt/nuts. Commodity spillage on the side shell of NATX 231217 was cleaned. No ground impact from spillage was reported. Response was concluded by 1647 hrs. CDT, 4/28/2014. The intact shipper seal at the manway closure was replaced by seal numbered 9707693.

column168: K & I EXPRESS CONTACTED ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT AND REPORTED THAT A TRAILER WAS MAKING A DELIVERY AT THE ABOVE REFERENCED LOCATION, WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD LEAKED, APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS OF A PAINT MATERIAL, K&I REQUESTED THAT A CREW BE MOBILIZED TO THE LOCATION.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT IT HAD BEEN CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  UPON ARRIVAL THE CLEANUP CREW STATED THEY WOULD CLEAN THE IMPACTED DRUMS AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE, THEN SEE IF GRIEF, INC WOULD STILL ACCEPTED THEM.  THEY ALSO LOCATED THE LEAKING DRUM WHICH APPEARED TO HAVE A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM POSSIBLY CAUSED BY A NAIL OR OTHER SHARP OBJECT.  THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVERPACK.  THE CLEANUP CREW THEN SPREAD OIL DRY ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER TO SOLIDIFY THE LIQUID.  THEY THEN USED SHOVELS AND PLACED THE IMPACTED ABSORBENT INTO TWO 55-GALLON DRUMS.  THE FREIGHT WAS CLEANED WELL ENOUGH FOR GRIEF TO ACCEPT.  THE OVERPACK WITH THE LEAKING DRUM AND TWO 55-GALLON DRUMS CONTAINING CLEANUP DEBRIS WERE LEFT ON THE TRAILER FOR K&I TO PROPERLY DISPOSE OF.

column168: Driver ariged at the consignee to offload. The product was Sodium Nitrate Liquor (40%). The driver hooked up to offload and began pressurizing the tank. The trailer was not in a containment area. The customer brought out a containment field to contain the product and captured approximately 3 gallons. The customer put this product in their storage. Approximately 5 ounces of the material was released to the top and side of the tote. The puncture in the tote was patched with 3B putty and accepted by the customer.

A call was received on 04/11/2014 with a question as to why a car with 1993 placards did not have hazardous materials shipment information associated with the car.  Upon further investigation this car was shipped as a non hazardous commodity with a STCC of 3742218. After talking with the shipper and reviewing the MSDS, the shipper, Global Energy, stated the car was billed improperly and it would need to be updated with proper billing along with 6 other cars. The proper billing was received by UPRR with the proper STCC of 4910185. This car then continued in transportation.
column169: No additional comments.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Threads Worn or Cross Threaded
column168: Car was observed leaking at the base of the 3 inch liquid valve flange within the combination housing.  3 flange nuts were tightened approximately three quarter turn each; the 4th nut was stripped which prevented it from being tightened.  A secondary nut was threaded onto the exposed threaded stud and tightened which secured the valve from further leakage. The shipper will apply for an OTMA-1 to move the car for off loading. Upon being off loaded, the car will be shopped for replacement of the threaded stud and nut assembly.
column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves, fittings and closures are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of liquid, vapor or gas while car is in transportation.

column168: NATX 301200 was reported to be leaking vapor from the manway. The cause of the release was a missing manway gasket. The gasket was replaced and the car continued in transportation.

column168: On April 28, 2014, a 55-gallond drum containing UN1193 Methyl Ethyl Ketone Solution was punctured resulting in the release of an estimated one pint of product to the floor of a trailer. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site for cleanup activities.The damaged drum was overpacked for continued transportation.

On  April 15, 2014, a Covenant Transport Group trailer experienced the release of 2 ounces of UN1133 from a damaged 1 gallon container. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site. Absorbents were applied to the impacted trailer floor and worked in thoroughly.

On April 16, 2014, a 55-gallon drum containing UN3109 Organic Peroxide was damaged due to a load shift resulting in the release of a approximately 55 gallons of product to the trailer floor and the roadway below. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site and performed cleanup activities.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 6:20 AM EST ON APRIL 10, 2014, OPERATOR MARK GALENO WAS OPERATING STRAIGHT CARGO TANK TRUCK (SINGLE PRODUCT COMPARTMENT) UNIT #595. UNIT #595 WAS TOWING A 1998 WELD-IT CARGO TANK PUP TRAILER, (TWO PRODUCT COMPARTMENTS). THE OPERATOR MARK GALENO WAS DRIVING IN A SOUTHERN DIRECTION ON SOUTH FERDON BLVD, ALSO KNOWN AS FLORIDA STATE RD 85. AS HE NAVIGATED THE LEFT HAND TURN ONTO THE EASTBOUND 1-10 ON-RAMP, THE PUP TRAILER (UNIT #207A) WHICH WAS CARRYING 3800 GALLONS OF GASOLINE IN THE REAR COMPARTMENT ROLLED OVER ON ITS RIGHT SIDE, STOPPING UPSIDE DOWN. MARK GALENO IMMEDIATELY STOPPED AND SHUT OFF UNIT #595 AND CALLED 911 TO REPORT THE ACCIDENT. A NEARBY POLICE OFFICER RESPONDING TO THE ACCIDENT STOPPED TRAFFIC FROM ENTERING THE EASTBOUND 1-10 ON-RAMP AND MOVED MARK GALENO AWAY FROM THE SCENE. UNIT#207A BEGAN LEAKING GASOLINE ONTO THE ROADWAY AND INTO A NEARBY DRAINAGE CULVERT. MARK GALENO CALLED TAI GUSTMAN, EASTERN OPERATIONS MANAGER, WHO THEN PUT INTO PLAY THE LAMB FUELS, INC "POST-ACCIDENT PROTOCOL", AND PROCEEDED VIA CAR TO THE ACCIDENT SCENE FROM OCALA, FLORIDA. THE PUP TRAILER'S SECOND COMPARTMENT DOT 406 DOME LID BURST OPEN RELEASING 3800 GALLONS OF GASOLINE TO THE ROADWAY AND ADJOINING DRAINAGE DITCH. LAMB FUELS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS CALLED, AND SWS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WERE ON SCENE WITH A COUPLE OF HOURS STARTING THE CLEAN UP PROCESS. AS OF TODAY 5/8/2014 REMEDIATION WORK IS STILL TAKING PLACE.
column169: IT HAS BEEN DEEMED BY LAMB FUELS, INC'S SAFETY & COMPLIANCE MANAGER THAT THIS WAS A PREVENTABLE ACCIDENT IN THAT THE OPERATOR MARK GALENO DID NOT EXERCISE SOUND JUDGMENT OR FORESEE THAT LOADING THE TRAILER WITH PRODUCT ONLY IN THE REAR COMPARTMENT WOULD ADVERSELY AFFECT THE WAY THE COMBINATION UNIT WOULD ACT, COUPLE WITH THE SPEED (APPRX. 25MPH) WHEN HE MADE THE LEFT HAND TURN ONTO THE INTERSTATE 10 ON RAMP. IN LIGHT OF THIS ACCIDENT, IT IS THE RECOMMENDATION OF THE SAFETY & COMPLIANCE MANAGER THAT THE ENTIRE LAMB FUELS FLEET OF DIVERS RECEIVE IMMEDIATE REMEDIAL TRAINING IN THE FOLLOWING FORMS: FMCSA/PHMSA "CARGO TANK ROLLOVER PREVENTION" VIDEO, ALL DRIVERS SHALL COMPLETE FOR JJ KELLER, INC WEB BASED COURSES DIRECTLY RELATED TO THE ROLLOVER ACCIDENT, CARGO TANK LOADING CONFIGURATIONS AND HAVE A ROAD TEST/RIDE ALONG COMPLETED BY THEIR RESPECTIVE LOCAL REGIONAL MANAGER. LAMB FUELS HAS INITIATED AN ALL-HANDS SAFETY STAND DOWN AND COMPANY WIDE CONFERENCE CALL WITH ALL EMPLOYEES TO CONVEY THE MAGNITUDE OF THIS ACCIDENT.

column168: A call was received from FRA inspector Scott Hoose stating he observed loaded hazmat tank car GATX 50884, UN 2924, Waste, Flammable Liquids, Corrosive N.O.S., 3 (8), PG III, leaking from the manway nosel of the car. A  closer inspection revealed that the manway gasket was incorrectly applied and rolled under the manway cover and pinched. Product was spilled out onto the top of the  tank car and down the side. This defect was reported to the carrier for corrective action. A represenative from the receiver corrected the condition.

column168: (A)At approximately 13:57 on April 30, 2014 the CSXT HG train dispatcher advised that the KO8227 was stopped in emergency and that fire was coming from the middle of the train near MP CAB 145.7 along the James River in Lynchburg Va. A total of 18 cars were derailed, with three in the James River. CBTX 741712 was breeched during the derailment and its contents were consumed by fire. A total of 300 people were evacuated for a period of time. CSXT personnel along with contractors and consultants responded. The NTSB and the FRA are investigating the incident. (B) On April 30, 2014 at approximately 19:00 personnel at the scene of the derailment in Lynchburg Va. discovered tank car CTCX 743023 leaking from the base of the liquid line while car was derailed on its side. CSXT HazMat personnel tried to tighten liquid line valve to stop the leak, personnel were able to slow the leak. Do to the car being involved in the derailment, the car was righted and transferred to another receiving car. The car is under legal hold by the NTSB. Once car is released by NTSB and CSX, shipper will need to apply for a OTMA to have valve fixed.    NARRI=283  5X(5+5+0)X(2X0)=100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: RON FIDLER PICKED UP TWO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANKS FROM CONSERV FS, INC LOCATION AT 20515 HARMONY ROAD MARENGO ILLINOIS. THE TANKS WERE NUMBERS 1507 AND 1510 AND WERE BOTH 1450 GALLON TANKS AND PICKED UP BY MR.FIDLER IN MID AFTERNOON. MR. FIDLER PROCEED WEST ON HARMONY ROAD TO THE INTERSECTION OF HARMONY ROAD AND ROUTE 23 SOUTH OF MARENGO. HE PROCEEDED IN THE DIRECTION OF THE FARM SOUTH ON ROUTE 23 TOWARDS THE ROUTE 23 AND ROUTE 72 INTERSECTION EAST OF GENOA.    SOMETHING HAPPENED ON ROUTE 23 ABOUT A MILE NORTH OF THE INTERSECTION OF ROUTE 72 WHERE THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED. ONE NURSE TANK ENDED UP OFF THE RUNNING GEAR AND SOMEWHAT UPSIDE DOWN IN THE WEST DITCH. THE OTHER TANK ENDED UP WITH THE FRONT AXLE REMOVED BUT WAS LAYING ON ITS SIDE. MR. FIDLER NOTIFIED AUTHORITIES AND NOTIFIED CONSERV. HE STATED THAT THERE WAS SOME RELEASING AND STAYED AT A SAFE DISTANCE.  JEFF KIMMEL RESPONDED FOR CONSERV TO THE LOCATION OF THE ACCIDENT. I WAS NOTIFIED OF THE ACCIDENT WHEN JEFF WAS ON SCENE. JEFF COMMUNICATED TO MR. FIDLER THAT THE PROPER NOTIFICATIONS NEEDED TO BE MADE AND GAVE HIM THE LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL RESPONSE TELEPHONE NUMBERS. THE ARRIVING AUTHORITIES BLOCKED A SECTION OF ROUTE 23 OFF TO TRAFFIC. THE AUTHORITIES REQUESTED MUTUAL AID FROM THE HAZMAT TEAM FROM DEKALB. JEFF SURVEYED THE SCENE FROM A SAFE DISTANCE AND COMMUNICATED THAT IT APPEARED THE TANK IN THE DITCH WAS RELEASING VAPOR FROM THE LIQUID WITHDRAWAL VALVE FROM FRONT OF THE TANK BUT COULD NOT GET CLOSE ENOUGH AT THIS TIME.    JEFF STAYED AT A SAFE DISTANCE AND TOLD AUTHORITIES HE WOULD BE AVAILABLE FOR CONSULTATION FOR THE HAZMAT TEAM. DEKALB HAZMAT ARRIVED ON SCENE AND SURVEYED SITUATION. AFTER A PERIOD OF TIME THEY CONSULTED WITH JEFF. THEY DECIDED TO LEAVE SCENE. CONFIRMATION HAS BEEN MADE THAT IT IS THE LIQUID WITHDRAWAL VALVE WHERE THE VAPOR IS RELEASING FROM IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT ROLL CAGE THAT PROTECTS THIS VALVE WAS SEVERELY DAMAGED. IT IS MY UNDERSTANDING AT THIS POINT WE WERE ASKED TO SAFELY CLEAR SCENE. JEFF HAS MANY YEARS OF HANDS ON EXPERIENCE WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. HE ALSO PROVIDES TRAINING TO FIREFIGHTERS IN REGARDS TO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AND HE IS ALSO A FIREFIGHTER HIMSELF. HIS PLAN IS TO USED A VAPOR PUMP ON BOTH TANKS TO REMOVE AS MUCH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA AS POSSIBLE. HE MOBILIZES HIS EMPLOYEE GROUP AND EQUIPMENT TO TRY TO ACCOMPLISH THIS TASK.    TWO EMPTY ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANKS WERE BROUGHT TO THE SCENE TO TRANSFER THIS PRODUCT IN TO. A WHEEL LOADER IS ALSO BROUGHT TO SCENE TO REMOVE DAMAGE EQUIPMENT FROM ROADWAY. THE PROCESS IS STARTED TO REMOVE PRODUCT FROM TANKS. AUTHORITIES EXPRESS CONCERN ABOUT THE LENGTH OF TIME THIS PROCESS IS TAKING. THIS PROCEDURES TAKES AN EXTENDED AMOUNT OF TIME. ONCE THE UPRIGHT TANK WAS EMPTIED THAT TANK WAS REMOVED FROM THE ROADWAY TO ADJACENT FIELD. THE DAMAGED TANK HAS THE LIQUID WITHDRAWAL VALVE SHEARED OFF AT THIS POINT THE VALVE IS DESIGNED TO SHEAR AT RIGHT ABOVE THE BUILT IT EXCESS FLOW VALVE.    THESE VALVES ARE DESIG

UPON ARRIVAL THE CREW NOTED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE LOWER EDGE OF THE TOTE, AND HAD BEEN A SLOW STEADY LEAK.  IT APPEARED THAT THE PALLET BROKE UNDER THE WEIGHT OF THE TOTE CAUSING A PART THE PALLET TO PUNCTURE THE TOTE.  THE MATERIAL WAS STARTING TO LEAK OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER AND THE CREW PLACED A COUPLE OF BAGS OF OIL DRY UNDER THE DRIPS, TO PREVENT ANY GROUND CONTAMINATION.    THE CREW THEN USED UNDAMAGED TOTE PROVIDED BY THE BEAVER EXPRESS TERMINAL TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL USING GRAVITY FEED METHOD.  ONCE THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED, THE CREW SPREAD OIL DRY INSIDE THE TRAILER AND BEGAN TO ABSORB THE FREE LIQUID.    ONCE THE FREE LIQUID HAD BEEN ABSORBED, THE CREW PLACED THE IMPACTED OIL DRY INTO TWO 55-GALLON DRUMS FOR LATER DISPOSAL.
column169: ENSURE THAT TOTES ARE ON GOOD PALLETS WITH NO SHARP OR PROTRUDING OBJECTS.

column168: DRIVER WAS LOOKING AT THE OHIO STATE POLICE OFFICER CONDUCTING A TRAFFIC STOP, FAILED TO PAY ATTENTION TO THE ROADWAY AND REAR-ENDED A TOW TRUCK. DUE TO THE ACCIDENT THE LOAD OF TOTES IN THE TRAILER HAD ALL SHIFTED FORWARD CAUSING ONE TOTE TO COMPLETELY RUPTURE AND RELEASE ALL 275 GALLONS A SECOND TOTE REMAINED INTACT UNTIL IT WAS REMOVED VIA PALLET-JACK AT WHICH POINT IT RELEASED ITS CONTENTS EXPELLING ANOTHER 275 GALLONS. THE CREW REMOVED FOUR ADDITIONAL TOTES THAT WERE DAMAGED AND SUSPECTED TO BE UNSAFE FOR TRANSPORT.    THE RELEASED PRODUCT WAS SQUEEGEED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND COLLECTED IN 55-GALLON OPEN TOP DRUMS. THE CREW CONTINUED TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER AND INSPECT THE REMAINING TOTES. TEN SHIPPABLE TOTES WERE RELOADED ONTO ANOTHER TRAILER AND REMOVED FROM THE SITE.    A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER AND IMPACTED THE GRASS AND SOIL ALONG HIGHWAY 33.  THE AREA WAS EXCAVATED AND RESTORED BACK TO ITS ORIGINAL CONDITION.  ALL WASTE ITEMS WERE REMOVED FROM THE SITE AND SEND TO LOCAL LANDFILL FOR FINAL PROCESSING.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred. While offloading, a faulty hose resulted in the loss of approximately 3 barrels of crude oil. Free product released to the soil within the loading area, and migrated approximately 160 feet down gradient to a soil ditch with free standing water. USES was dispatched by Catamount Transport to perform the cleanup. Upon assessment of the site, Sunoco contracted their response contractor EMS Global to respond. EMS Global recovered the free product and water from the immediate area, excavated the impacted soil, and restored site to preexisting condition. Free product did not migrate off site, or threaten waters of the state. Disposal was coordinated by EMS Global in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations. There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Catamount Transport LLC will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

REVIEW OF ANY ACCIDENT WITH PERSONNEL IS IMPORTANT FOR POSSIBLE ITEMS THAT COULD AVOID BAD SITUATIONS.

CN Transportation employees observed product coming from the top of tank car TCDX 13245(L / Sulfuric Acid, Spent) during a train inspection at CN Brookhaven Yard, Brookhaven, Ms.  All appropriate departments notified, track was protected. CN's response team responded and observed liquid coming from below the liquid valve cap. Pressure was relieved from the railcar using the vapor valve. Product stopped leaking from the liquid valve when pressure was relieved. The cap on the liquid valve was checked for tightness. Immediately upon contact with the cap, the cap broke in half. The cap was replaced. Product on the car was neutralized and washed off. Tank car released for movement.

column168: 4/23/14: At 12:04AM, CR Trainmaster C. Taylor contacted CR Risk Manager A. Richter advising Car Department Inspector noted tank car TEIX 25003, load, Flammable Liquid NOS (Aviation Gasoline) to be wet on both sides of the car, while performing an inspection of planned outbound train SP18, in CR's Pavonia Yard, Camden, NJ.    Emergency response contractor Hepaco-React was dispatched to the scene.  No product on ground and car only leaked while being moved.  Further inspection by Hepaco-React noted of the 6 manway cover securement bolts on the manway cover, 2 securement bolts (one at hinge and the other at the handle) were not applied; the remaining 4 securement bolts were applied but not even tool tight; and the manway cover gasket, while by appearance looked in good condition while applied, crumbled apart when removed.    Gasket was replaced with a compatible gasket, cover closed, all manway cover securement bolts applied and made tool tight.      4/24/14: Sides of car affected by the product spillage were cleaned and deconned and car okayed for continued movement to original consignee.
column169: Contrary to Section 172.604, the displayed 24-hour emergency response phone number ("856-848-3719") on the movement waybill was called by CR's A. Richter at 12:24AM, after being notified of the incident, but was advised by the person answering that this number was merely a 24-hour dispatch number and the person answering would have someone call back.  A company representative called back at 12:49AM.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. VEHICLE INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT, RESULTING IN A ROLL-OVER. AS A RESULT, APPROXIMATELY 1000 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED FROM THE PORTABLE TANK. THE FREE LIQUID IMPACTED SOIL AND A DRY DITCH. LOCAL FIRST RESPONDERS DEPLOYED SAND TO CONTAIN THE FREE LIQUID. ATLANTIC RESPONSE, INC. OF VINELAND, NEW JERSEY WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. ATLANTIC RESPONSE, INC. DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CONTAIN THE FREE LIQUID. ATLANTIC RESPONSE, INC. REMOVED THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING TANK. ATLANTIC RESPONSE, INC. EXCAVATED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND PLACED INTO A ROLL-OFF BOX FOR DISPOSAL. ATLANTIC RESPONSE, INC. COORDINATED DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, Miracle Chemical will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: On 4/8/14 after 12:00 AM we had a spill of sodium hydroxide from the sodium hydroxide tank in the south end of the building. The operator was transferring sodium hydroxide solution from a rail car, SHPX 201487. The operator was not monitoring the level indicator for the tank and the tank was overfilled. The release lasted for approximately 5 minutes. The area of the spill was approximately 10 feet wide by 40 feet long for an approximate area of 400 square feet. The temperature at the time of the spill was approximately 37°F, which was below the freezing point (53.6°F) of sodium hydroxide 50%. The caustic that spilled outside froze upon contact with the ground forming a boundary layer. We were able to recover most of the spill by neutralizing with citric acid, powder, and floor dry. The citric acid and floor dry was used to absorb the liquid portion of the spill and allowed for us to recover the material before it absorbed into the ground. The hazmat responders poured the floor dry on top of the spill and then mixed the floor dry into the liquid sodium hydroxide to absorb all the liquid sodium hydroxide from the top of the sodium hydroxide that had frozen on the ground. The floor dry was put into open top drums and open top totes (totes that had the top cut off). A contractor came in with a backhoe and the frozen sodium hydroxide and the gravel that was contaminated was removed and placed in open top drums and totes. The totes were transferred into drums and prepared to ship to our hazardous waste disposal company.
column169: The operator was disciplined for not properly monitoring the unloading process. A root cause analysis was performed. Based on the results from the root cause we will evaluate the use of an automatic safety systems that will stop the flow of material into the tank. The cost of such system will be entered into the capital budget plan.

column168: MAY 2, 2014    MR. TONY WALKER  REGIONAL DIRECTOR. REGION 4  TEXAS COMMISSION ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY  2309 GRAVEL DR.  FORT WORTH, TEXAS 76118-6951           RE:  30-DAY REPORT         INCIDENT REPORT NO. 2014-1046         PWS ID NO. 0430044    DEAR MR WALKER:           PURSUANT TO 30 TEX. ADMIN. CODE ("TAC") 327.3 AND 327.5 NORTH TEXAS MUNICIPAL WATER DISTRICT ("NTMWD" OR THE "DISTRICT") HEREBY PROVIDES THIS WRITTEN SUBMISSION REGARDING ADDITIONAL INFORMATION CONCERNING A RELASE ONTO PROPERTY OWNED BY NTMWD.  PURSUANT TO 30 TAC 327.3 (B).  THE DISTRICT’S "INITIAL REPORT" WAS FILED VIA TELEPHONE CALL TO THE STATE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER AT 1-800-832-8224 ON APRIL 2, 2014.  AND ASSIGN REPORT NO. 2014-1046.  THE INITIAL REPORT DESCRIBED A RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF HYDROFLUOROSILICIC ACID (23-25%) ("FLOURIDE SOLUTION") THAT OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 AM ON APRIL 2, 2014.  THE INFORMATION IN THAT REPORT IS CORRECT TO THE BEST OF THE DISTRICT'S KNOWLEDGE AND BELIEFE AND IS INCORPORATED BY REFERENCE HEREIN.  THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION SUPPLEMENTS THE INITIAL REPORT.  BUT TO THE EXTENT THIS REPORT IS NOT CONSISTENT WITH THE INITIAL REPORT.  THIS LETTER SUPERSEDES AND REPLACES THE PRIOR INFORMATION.                   SINCE SUBMITTING THE INITIAL REPORT.  NTMWD HAS COMPLETED AN INVESTIGATION INTO THE EVENTS LEADING UP TO THE RELEASE.  INCLUDING THE CAUSES OF THE RELEASE. STEPS TO PREVENT A SIMILAR INCIDENT FROM OCCURRING IN THE FUTURE.  AND THE NEED FOR, AND STATS OF. REMEDIATION.  AS DESCRIBED IN THE INITIAL REPORT. AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 AM ON APRIL 2, 2014. DURING THE FILLING OF A DOUBLE WALLED FLUORIDE TANK AT THE DISTRICT'S WATER TREATMENT PLANT NO. 3 ("WTP3"). THE TRUCK DRIVER DELIVERING FLUORIDE SOLUTION TO WTP3 NOTICED THAT FLUORIDE SOLUTION WAS OVERFLOWING FROM THE TANK.  HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE LINE FEEDING THE TANK AND NOTIFIED PLANT STAFF.  PLANT STAFF PLACED A BERN TO PREVENT THE SOLUTION FROM LEAVING THE SITE.           A REMEDIATION CONSULTANT (AMEC) AND CONTRACTOR (USA ENVIRONMENT. L.P.) WERE CALLED TO THE SITE TO ASSES THE SITUATION AND PROVIDE ADDITIONAL RECOMMENDATIONS.  IN ACCORDANCE WITH AMEC'S RECOMMENDATIONS. PROTECTIVE PLASTIC WAS PLACED OVER THE AFFECTED AREA TO FURTHER PREVENT RUN-OFF.  USA EXCAVATED AND STOCKPILED THE FLUORIDE SOLUTION IMPACTED SOIL ON APRIL 4, 2014 AND AMEC COLLECTED CONFIRMATION SAMPLES AND DETERMINED THAT THE CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETE AND BACKGROUND LEVELS WERE REACHED.  COPIES OF BACKGROUND SAMPLES, CONFIRMATION SAMPLES AND WASTE CHARACTERIZATION SAMPLES WERE ATTACHED.  ALSO ATTACHED IS AN AERIAL KEY AND A PHOTO LOG OF THE RESPONSE.  THE DISTRICT IS ARRANGING FOR DISPOSAL OF THE IMPACTED SOIL AND EXPECTS DISPOSAL TO BE COMPLETE BY MAY 16, 2014/           FOLLOWING ITS INVESTIGATION. NTMWD HAS TAKEN STEPS TO ENSURE THAT SUCH A RELEASE DOES NOT OCCUR IN THE FUTURE.  SPECIFICALLY, THE DISTRICT DETERMINED THAT THE OVERFLOW OCCURRED BECAUSE A LEVEL INDICATOR MALFUNCTIONED. column168: MR. WILLIAMS WAS DELIVERING TWO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANKS FROM DEKALB TO MAPLE PARK FOR A CUSTOMER. MR. WILLIAMS ENTERED THE INTERSECTION OF ROUTE 38 AND COUNTY LINE ROAD AND TURNED TO THE NORTH WHEN HE NOTICED THE REAR TANK HAD OVERTURNED AFTER THE INTERSECTION. HE CALLED 911 AND POLICE AND FIRE ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. HE ALSO CALLED CONSERV SUPERVISOR TO COME TO THE SCENE. THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT LEAKING OUT OF THE VAPOR VALVE ON THE OVERTURNED TANK. CONSERV SUPERVISOR WITH APPROVAL OF FIRE DEPARTMENT APPROACHED TANK AND CLOSED VALVE THAT WAS LEAKING.  VALVE APPEARED TO BE JARRED SLIGHTLY OPEN, CAUSED BY THE TANK BEING OVERTURNED.  TANK WAS UP-RIGHTED AND RETURNED TO DEKALB LOCATION TO BE EMPTIED AND PLACED OUT OF SERVICE UNTIL FURTHER EXAMINATION. CONSERV SUPERVISOR HANDLED DISCIPLINARY ACTION WITH MR. WILLIAMS IN REGARDS TO SPEED THAT APPEARED TO BE THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT. LESS THAN 2 GALLONS WERE RELEASED AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT.
column169: MORE TRAINING IN REGARDS TO DRIVING AND TO SLOW DOWN MAY HAVE BEEN A WAY TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: THE FIRST INCIDENT OCCURRED ON THE 11TH AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 PM, WHEN A PENN TANK LINES DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY IDENTIFY THE PREMIUM TANK DURING THE DELIVERY PROCESS. THIS RESULTED IN APPROXIMATELY 700 GALLONS OF REGULAR UL GASOLINE TO BE DELIVERED INTO THE PREMIUM UL GASOLINE TANK.  WHILE MAKING THE DELIVERY, THE DRIVER REALIZED THE ERROR AND STOPPED THE FLOW OF PRODUCT. THE DRIVER CONTACTED THE TERMINAL AND ADDITIONAL PERSONNEL FROM PENN TANK LINES RESPONDED TO THE SITE. THE TANK WAS SCHEDULED FOR AN IMMEDIATE PUMP OVER OF PREMIUM UL INTO THE REGULAR UL TANKS. DURING THE PROCESS OF TRANSFERRING THE PRODUCT, THE CONTENTS OF THE PREMIUM TANK WERE PUMPED INTO ONLY ONE OF THE REGULAR TANKS. THIS TRANSFER OCCURRED WITH NO SPILL OR OTHER KNOWN ISSUES AT THAT TIME.  THE NEXT EVENING, ON SATURDAY, THE 12TH A DELIVERY WAS SCHEDULED INTO THE SAME WAWA STORE LOCATION AT APPROXIMATELY 9:00 PM. DURING THE DELIVERY, THERE WAS AN APPARENT PRESSURE ISSUE EXPERIENCED, WHICH MAY HAVE CAUSED THE ACCIDENTAL RELEASE OF PRODUCT. IT APPEARS THAT THE OVERFILL PROTECTION FLAPPER CLOSED AND DUE TO EXCESS PRESSURE THE PRODUCT ESCAPED FROM THE CONNECTION TO THE UST. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE INTERNAL VALVE SYSTEM ON THE TRAILER AND MADE ATTEMPTS TO MINIMIZE THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT. DUE TO THE EXCESS PRESSURE IN THE TANK, THE PRODUCT CONTINUED TO FLOW FROM THE FILL AREA. THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED AT APPROXIMATELY SEVENTY-FIVE (75) GALLONS. THE PRODUCT ENTERED INTO TWO SEPARATE STORM DRAINS BUT INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE IMMEDIATE AREA OF THE DRAINS AND DID NOT TRAVEL FURTHER OR IMPACT ANY SOIL OR WATERWAYS.  LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL WAS NOTIFIED BY WAWA REPRESENTATIVES AND RESPONDED TO THE SITE WITH REMEDIATION EQUIPMENT AND PERSONNEL, INCLUDING ONE TRUCK AND THREE WORKERS.  THEY SUBSEQUENTLY CALLED A FOURTH PERSON TO BRING AN AIR PUMP TO REMOVE SLUDGE AND GASOLINE FROM THE TWO STORM DRAINS. AFTER REVIEW AND TESTING, LEWIS ENVIRONMENTAL REPRESENTATIVES CONFIRMED THE PRODUCT IN THE DRAIN WAS CONTAINED AND HAD NOT TRAVELED FURTHER. TWO FIFTY-FIVE (55) GALLON DRUMS WERE UTILIZED FOR CONTAINMENT AND REMOVAL OF THE SLUDGE, PRODUCT & SPILL MATERIALS USED.  THE PA DEP WAS ALSO NOTIFIED (BOB BOWER BAUER @ 484-250-5900). THE DEP WAS GIVEN THE FOLLOWING INFORMATION: "ESTIMATED SPILL PER OUR PEOPLE ON SCENE AT 50 TO 75 GALLONS. REGULAR MADE IT TO TWO STORM SEWERES AND WAS ESTIMATED THERE WAS 20 TO 30 GALLONS IN EACH DRAIN. THE OUTLETS FROM THE SEWER DRAINS TO THE STREET ARE ELEVATED SO NO PRODUCT WAS SAID TO HAVE ESCAPED FROM THE DRAINS."  THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS ALSO NOTIFIED AND GIVEN THE SAME INFORMATION. (REPORT# 1079638)  THE FOLLOWING UP INVESTIGATION BY PENN TANK LINES IDENTIFIED THAT FOLLOWING:  1. DURING THE PROCESS OF PUMPING OVER THE PRODUCT ON APRIL 11TH, 2014, THE DRIVER PUMPED THE PRODUCT FROM THE PREMIUM TANK INTO THE ONE REGULAR TANK (TANK#3).  THE DRIVER WAS USING THE TRACTOR PUMP TO DIRECTLY

column168: ON APRIL 15, 2014, AT APPROXIMATELY 1:00 AM CDT, A VEHICLE OPERATED BY BHI WAS TRAVELING NEAR THE HWY-13, 20 MILES NORTH OF CRAIG WHEN A DEER RAN INTO THE ROAD.  THE DRIVER OF THE UNIT VEERED THE UNIT AWAY FROM THE DEER, WHICH CAUSE ONE 300 GALLON TOTE OF BLEACH 12 1/2% TO FALL FROM THE UNIT ONTO THE SOIL SHOULDER. THE TOTE LANDED ON ITS SIDE AND BEGAN LEAKING FLUID FROM ITS VENT CAP. APPROXIMATELY 200 GALLONS OF BLEACH 12 1/2% LEAKED FROM THE TOTE TO THE SOIL SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY.  AT APPROXIMATELY 2:21 AM CDT, MR. BRETT BAKER OF BHI RETRAINED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES, LC (CES) TO MANAGE THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP ON THEIR BEHALF.  BASED ON THE AVAILABLE INFORMATION, THE CES INCIDENT MANAGER RETAINED ECOS ENVIRONMENTAL TO ASSESS THE SITE AND INITIATE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  THE CREW FROM ECOS MOBILIZED TO THE SITE. UPON ARRIVAL, THE CREW MET WITH FIRST RESPONDER PERSONNEL TO ASSESS THE IMPACTED LOCATION. THE IMPACT COVERED AN APPROXIMATE 30 FOOT BY 10 FOOT AREA ALONG THE SOIL SHOULDER. THE CREW BEGAN BY PUMPING LIQUID REMAINING IN THE TOTE INTO DRUMS FOR TRANSPORTATION AND DISPOSAL.  THE IMPACTED SOIL WAS COVERED IN POLY SHEETING TO PREVENT MIGRATION OF THE FLUID WHILE PERMITS TO EXCAVATE COULD BE OBTAINED.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: AT APPROX 1415 ON 4/29/14 TERMINAL OPERATOR HAD COMPLETED TRANSLOADING LPG FROM GLNX 33467 TO TANK TRUCK. OPERATOR CLOSED VALVE AND VERIFIED TIGHT. UPON DISCONNECTING HOSE HAD SPRAY OF LPG LIQUID/VAPOR FROM TOP LIQUID VALVE ON A END.  OPERATOR CLIMBED DOWN FROM CAR AND NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR OF UNCONTROLLED LEAK AND THEN CALLED 911. WASHINGTON FD RESPONDED IN SUPPORTING ROLE. COMPANY NOTIFIED SPECIALIZED RESPONSE SERVICES (SRS) WHO THEN DISPATCHED HEPACO INC. TO SCENE. SUNOCO LOGISTICS MANAGEMENT AND SAFETY DEPARTMENT REPRESENTATIVE ARRIVED ON SITE APPROX 0200 4/30/14.  HEPACO PERSONNEL INSTALLED THREADED PIPE INTO LIQUID VALVE AND CLOSED OFF FLOW. REMAINING LIQUID OFFLOADED FROM GLNX 33467 TO TANK TRUCK. CAR WAS THEN PURGED WITH NITROGEN AND ALL RESIDUAL VAPOR DESTROYED WITH FLARE.  CAR IS AT WASHINGTON TERMINAL IN AN INERT CONDITION AWAITING SUBMISSION OF OTMA FOR SHOP. PROTECTIVE HOUSING IS SEALED WITH HEPACO CAR SEAL AND HAS BEEN UNDISTURBED SINCE INCIDENT. AWAITING SHOP FOR INSPECTION OF VALVE.    UPON COMPLETION OF TRANSLOAD GLNX 33467 CONTAINED APPROX 7200 LIQUID GALLON LPG. DURATION OF RELEASE (THROUGH 2"ANGLE VALVE) APPROX 4 HOURS. OFFLOADED APPROX 2200 GALLON TO TRUCK, APPROX 5000 GALLON LOST TO ATMOSPHERE.T  HERE WAS NO FIRE AND NO INJURIES OF ANY KIND TO PERSONNEL.
column169: None. Suspect failed angle valve.

column168: ON APRIL 29, 2014 THE DRIVER OF THE PETROLEUM TRANSPORT WAS DELIVERING DIESEL FUEL TO A LARGE ABOVE GROUND STATIONARY DIESEL TANK. THE DRIVER ATTACHED THE DELIVERY HOSE FROM THE TRUCK PASSENGER SIDE TO THE TANK AND WAS SUPPOSED TO OPEN ALL VALVES INCLUDING VALVES ON THE TRUCK AND THE VALVE ON THE TANK. HE THOUGHT THE VALVE ON THE BULK TANK WAS OPEN AFTER CHECKING IT BUT THE VALVE TURNED OUT TO BE NOT OPEN.    THE DRIVER THEN RE-ENTERED THE CAB OF THE TRANSPORT AND ENGAGED THE PUMP. HE GOT OUT AND WENT AROUND TO THE PASSENGER SIDE OF THE TRUCK TO STAND BY WHILE THE DIESEL FUEL WAS BEING PUMPED OFF. AS HE GOT AROUND TO THE PASSENGER SIDE, HE SAW THAT THE HOSE AT THE TRUCK HAD SEPARATED FROM THE COUPLING BECAUSE OF THE PRESSURE BUILD UP IN THE HOSE AND CLOSED TANK VALVE AND SAW DIESEL BEING DISCHARGED ONTO THE GROUND.  HE THEN IMMEDIATELY WENT BACK TO THE DRIVER’S SIDE JUMPED INTO THE CAB AND DISENGAGED THE PUMP STOPPING THE FLOW OF DIESEL. THE ESTIMATED DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 10-15 SECONDS SPILLING AN ESTIMATED 200 GALLONS OF DIESEL. LOCAL MILL PERSONNEL WERE IMMEDIATELY SUMMONED. THEY BEGAN FORMING BARRICADES TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE AND STARTED CLEANING WITH ABSORBENT MATERIALS.
column169: WE HAVE WRITTIN PROCEDURES TO FOLLOW WHEN DELIVERING IN BULK STORAGE TANKS (ATTACHED). THERE WAS A FAILURE OF THE DRIVERS PART NOW FOLLOWING THE WRITTEN PROCEDURES WHICH WERE:  1.  NOT USING THE CORRECT HOSE MADE TO HANDLE THE PRESSURE.  2.  LEAVING A TANK VALVE SHUT THAT WAS SUPPOSED TO BE OPEN.  3.  NOT OPENING THE EXTERNAL TRUCK VALVE AS THE LAST OPERATION AFTER THE PUMP WAS ENGAGED TO MAKE SURE ALL CONNECTIONS WERE SECURE.    WE HAVE HAD THE ADDITIONAL DISCUSSIONS WITH OUR DRIVERS TO REINFORCE THE EXTREME IMPORTANCE IN FOLLOWING THE LOADING AND UNLOADING PROCEDURES AND DIRECTIVES.    PLEASE SEE ATTACHED UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

column168: Another shipment of freight was loaded on to a load deck. The freight was not properly strapped in and fell onto this shipment. The tote was punctured causing it to leak.  Due to the nature of the chemical, area isolated until emergency response team arrival.  Cleaned up by team.

WHILE TRAVELING AT APPROXIMATELY 65 MPH, OUR CTMV DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID A STOPPED VEHICLE PARTIALLY IN THE LANE OF TRAVEL AND THE CTMV'S REAR AXLES WENT ONTO THE SOFT SHOULDER. THIS CAUSED THE CTMV TO ROLL ROLLED OVER ABOUT 120 DEGREES TO THE RIGHT ONTO THE HIGHWAY SHOULDER. THE ROLLOVER PROTECTION DEVICES (CRASH BOX TOMBSTONES) DUG INTO THE MUDDY SOIL, WHICH IMPACTED THE ACCESSORIALS IN THE DOME AREA, INCLUDING THE PRESSURE RELIEF VENT (PRV.) THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT APPEARS TO HAVE CAUSED THE PRV TO OPEN, AND FOREIGN DEBRIS IN THE MUDDY SOIL KEPT THE PRV FROM IMMEDIATELY CLOSING. AS A RESULT, HAZMAT BEGAN LEAKING THROUGH THE OPEN PRV.  EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE DISPATCHED TO TRANSLOAD THE PRODUCT TO A RESCUE TRANSLOADED TO THE RESCUE CTMV FOR SUBSEQUENT DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE. THE DAMAGED CTMV WAS UPRIGHTED AND TOWED FORM THE SCENE. IMPACTED MEDIA WAS REMOVED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. A SUBSEQUENT INSPECTION OF THE PRV REVEALED THAT IT WAS NOT MECHANICALLY DAMAGED, AND THAT THE FOREIGN DEBRIS (STONES AND ROCKS) PREVENTED IT FROM RE-CLOSING AFTER THE IMPACT.  OUR REFERENCE 41166

column168: DRIVER NOTICED HE WAS LEAKING FLUID AND EXITED HIGHWAY & ENTERED LOVE’S TRUCK STOP PARKING LOT. UPON ENTERING LOT TANK CRACKED CAUSING LIQUID TO LEAK AT RATE OF AROUND 200 GAL PER HOUR. LOCAL FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED TO HELP CONTAIN SPILL & THEN BERKS COUNTY HAZMAT RESPONDER. CARRIER CONTACTED FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL WHO DISPATCHED PERSONNEL TO SCENE. SPILL WAS CONTAINED BY ADDING SAND & CREATING BERMS OF SAND. TANK CONTINUED TO RELEASE MATERIAL UNTIL AROUND 1200, 4/16/14 WHEN A SECOND ARRIVED AND WE WERE ABLE TO TRANSFER PRODUCT OFF LEAKING TRAILER TO ANOTHER TRAILER.
column169: WE ARE KEEPING "SPARE TRAILERS" EQUIPED WITH SPECIAL PUMPS THAT ALLOW PRODUCT TRANSFER IN CASE OF A LEAK. TANK WAS A LATE MODEL & SUFFERED A STRUCTURAL FAILURE THAT COULD NOT BE PREDICTED OR PREVENTED BY INSPECTION.

column168: MCF SYSTEMS ATLANTA, INC'S DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST ON HIGHWAY 78 NEAR TUPELO, MS AND REPORTED THAT HE APPARENTLY FELL ASLEEP AT THE WHEEL AND CROSSED OVER THE MEDIAN INTO THE WEST BOUND LANE STRIKING AN ONCOMING VEHICLE ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE.  THE VEHICLE WAS A 2014 INTERNATIONAL 35,000 GVW, STRAIGHT TRUCK OUTFITTED WITH A 26 FOOT DRY VAN BOX LOADED WITH 26 (15) GALLON CONTAINERS OF MIXED SLUDGE WASTE CONTAINING SPENT TETRACHLOROETHYLENE DRY CLEANER SOLVENT AND 7(55) GALLON DRUMS CONTAINING DRY CLEANING AND BODY WHOP WASTE. AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT SEVERAL CONTAINERS IN THE BOX SECTION OF THE TRUCK OF THE TRUCK COMPRESSED AND WERE TEMPORARILY DEFORMED ALLOWING LIQUID CONTENTS TO SEAP FROM THE TOPS OF SOME OF THE CONTAINERS. THE CONTAINERS WERE SECURED BY "LOAD-LOACKS" AND REMAINED IN PLACE AND INTACT. AFTER DISCUSSIONS WITH THE POLICE OFFICERS THAT RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT WE ASCERTAINED THAT THERE WERE SOME FLUIDS LEAKING FROM THE ENGINE OF THE ONE OF THE TRUCKS AS WELL AS FROM THE BOX SECTION OF THE TRUCK. WE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY, UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WHICH DISPATCHED A TEAM TO THE SITE AND UPON ARRIVAL RESPONDED TO CONTAIN ANY FURTHER LEAKING WITH ADSORBENT MATERIAL, PLACEMENT OF CONTAINERS TO COLLECT ADDITIONAL LIQUIDS LEAKING FROM THE BOX, CLEANING UP OF ANY MATERIALS ON THE ROADWAY AND PLACE A CONTAINMENT CURTAIN UNDER THE BOX TO CONTAIN ANY REMAINING LIQUID SEEPAGE.  AFTER THE SECURING THE BOX AND CONTAINING FURTHER LEAKAGE MCF PERSONNEL ENTERED THE VEHICLE BOX SECTION AND SECURED ALL CONTAINER LIDS, CLEANED CONTAINERS, THE FLOOR OF THE BOX AND CONTAINING FURTHER LEAKAGE MCF PERSONNEL ENTERED THE VEHICLE BOX SECTION AND SECURED ALL CONTAINER LIDS, CLEANED CONTAINERS, THE FLOOR OF THE BOX AND PLACED ALL CLEANUP MATERIALS IN APPROPRIATE DRUMS FROM REMOVAL.  THE LOAD AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE RETURNED TO MCF TRANSFER FACILITY AND ULTIMATELY TO THE DESIGNATED DISPOSAL FACILITY.
column169: ALL MCF HAZARDOUS WASTE DRIVERS/VEHICLES OPERATE WITH ELECTRONIC LOGGING SYSTEMS AND ARE MANAGED TO INSURE STRICT COMPLIANCE WITH HOURS OF SERVICE. ALTHOUGH THIS DRIVER WAS WELL WITHIN HIS HOURS-ON HE STILL EXPERIENCED THE EFFECTS OF FATIGUE OR ILLNESS. SINCE THIS INCIDENT WAS THE RESULT OF THE DRIVER REPORTING THAT HE HAD FALLEN ASLEEP WE HAVE REINFORCED THE IMPORTANCE TO ALL OF OUR DRIVERS TO BE AWARE OF SIGNS OF FATIGUE, DROWSINESS OR ILLNESS ALL OF WHICH CAN IMPAIR THE SAFE OPERATION OF A MOTOR VEHICLE IN A REST AREA OR OTHER SUITABLE PARKING AREA AND CALL THE OFFICE TO DISCUSS THE SITUATION WITH A SUPERVISOR AND THEN TAKE A NAP OR SHORT WALK. IN THIS INCIDENT THE CONTAINERS/LOAD WERE SECURED WITH PROPER LOAD LOCKING DEVISES WHICH MAINTAINED THE INTEGRITY OF THE CONTAINERS TO THE EXTENT POSSIBLE AND PREVENTED THE SPILLAGE OF A LARGER VOLUME OF LIQUIDS. THE PROCEDURES AND TECHNIQUES FOR PROPERTY SECURING A LOAD OF DRUMS WAS REVIEWED AND THE PARTICIPANTS PERFORMED SUPERVISED DEMONSTRATIONS EMPLOYING THE PROCEDURES.

column168: MCF SYSTEMS ATLANTA, INC'S DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST ON HIGHWAY 78 NEAR TUPELO, MS AND REPORTED THAT HE APPARENTLY FELL ASLEEP AT THE WHEEL AND CROSSED OVER THE MEDIAN INTO THE WEST BOUND LANE STRIKING AN ONCOMING VEHICLE ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE.  THE VEHICLE WAS A 2014 INTERNATIONAL 35,000 GVW, STRAIGHT TRUCK OUTFITTED WITH A 26 FOOT DRY VAN BOX LOADED WITH 26 (15) GALLON CONTAINERS OF MIXED SLUDGE WASTE CONTAINING SPENT TETRACHLOROETHYLENE DRY CLEANER SOLVENT AND 7(55) GALLON DRUMS CONTAINING DRY CLEANING AND BODY WHOP WASTE. AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT SEVERAL CONTAINERS IN THE BOX SECTION OF THE TRUCK OF THE TRUCK COMPRESSED AND WERE TEMPORARILY DEFORMED ALLOWING LIQUID CONTENTS TO SEAP FROM THE TOPS OF SOME OF THE CONTAINERS. THE CONTAINERS WERE SECURED BY "LOAD-LOACKS" AND REMAINED IN PLACE AND INTACT. AFTER DISCUSSIONS WITH THE POLICE OFFICERS THAT RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT WE ASCERTAINED THAT THERE WERE SOME FLUIDS LEAKING FROM THE ENGINE OF THE ONE OF THE TRUCKS AS WELL AS FROM THE BOX SECTION OF THE TRUCK. WE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY, UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WHICH DISPATCHED A TEAM TO THE SITE AND UPON ARRIVAL RESPONDED TO CONTAIN ANY FURTHER LEAKING WITH ADSORBENT MATERIAL, PLACEMENT OF CONTAINERS TO COLLECT ADDITIONAL LIQUIDS LEAKING FROM THE BOX, CLEANING UP OF ANY MATERIALS ON THE ROADWAY AND PLACE A CONTAINMENT CURTAIN UNDER THE BOX TO CONTAIN ANY REMAINING LIQUID SEEPAGE.  AFTER THE SECURING THE BOX AND CONTAINING FURTHER LEAKAGE MCF PERSONNEL ENTERED THE VEHICLE BOX SECTION AND SECURED ALL CONTAINER LIDS, CLEANED CONTAINERS, THE FLOOR OF THE BOX AND CONTAINING FURTHER LEAKAGE MCF PERSONNEL ENTERED THE VEHICLE BOX SECTION AND SECURED ALL CONTAINER LIDS, CLEANED CONTAINERS, THE FLOOR OF THE BOX AND PLACED ALL CLEANUP MATERIALS IN APPROPRIATE DRUMS FROM REMOVAL.  THE LOAD AND CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE RETURNED TO MCF TRANSFER FACILITY AND ULTIMATELY TO THE DESIGNATED DISPOSAL FACILITY.

column168: While unloading 8 - IBC from the carrier's truck, one of the IB(slipped off the forklift. The IBC was equipped with a pump and the discharge valve on the pump was damaged, causing 40 gallons of Gramoxone SL 2.0 (paraquat herbicide) to spill onto the soil. No damage occurred to the IBC, only to the valve on the pump. Absorbent materials were used to contain the spill and prevent spreading beyond the immediate area - approximately 20 feet x10 feet. An emergency contractor was called to excavate the impacted soil. All impacted soil was contained and shipped offsite as waste. Notification was made to the National Response Center due to the fact the reportable quantity for paraquat was released. Notification was also made to MS DEQ.
column169: Additional employee training to ensure any IBC being unloaded have all appurtenances secured, including pumps, hoses and any valves, prior to unloading.

column168: AWB 176-83636965 IAH/CMN forwarded as general cargo and when in transit in DXB found the packages with DG UN1956 RNG labels. Upon investigations revealed that the shipment in fact a DG shipment.
column169: Informed the agent SECURE GLOBAL LOGISTICS, 1045 GREENS PARKWAY, HOUSTON, TX 77067 and got revised set of AWB/DGD and subsiquently shipment forwarded to fibal destination with the approvals from U.S and U.A.E approvals.
column172: Box, wood or fiberboard not specified

column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: DRIVER WAS REPOSITIONING AN IBC OF 50% CAUSTIC SODA IN HIS TRAILER USING AN ELECTRIC PALLET JACK.  WHEN HE WAS ATTEMPTING TO TURN THE IBC AROUND FOR OFFLOADING, HE ACCIDENTALLY RAMMED IT AGAINST A STRAP BUCKLE THAT WAS SECURING DRUMS TO THE WALL OF THE TRAILER. THE STRAP BUCKLE PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE BLADDER OF THE IBC APPROX. 3" ACROSS LOCATED AROUND THE MIDLINE OF THE IBC. SOME OF THE MATERIAL IN THE IBC LEAKED TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE PARKING LOT OF THE DELIVERY LOCATION. ON-SITE RESPONDERS USED ANHYDROUS CITRIC TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILLED MATERIAL.
column169: THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE INIDICENT WAS DETERMINED TO BE POOR JUDGMENT BY THE DRIVER WHEN REPOSITIONING THE IBC FOR DELIVERY. INSTEAD OF MOVING THE DRUMS OUT OF THE WAY, HE LEFT THEM STRAPPED TO THE WALL IN THE AREA WHERE HE ATTEMPTED TO TURN THE TOTE AROUND. THIS REDUCED HIS AREA FOR TURNAROUND. ALL DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INFORMED THAT THEY ARE TO MOVE ANY PACKAGES THAT MAY INTERFERE WITH TURNING A TOTE AROUND IN THE TRAILER.

column169: ALWAYS BLOCK AND BRACE FREIGHT TO PREVENT MOVEMENT.

column168: AROUND 8:45-9:00 THE TONGUE BROKE OUT OF THE FRONT WAGON. 1 OF 2 BEING SPILLED IN THE FIELD BELONGING TO JOHN POPPE OF DICKEN, MO. THE HOSES WERE SPILLED APAPRT AND A CONSIDERABLE AMOUNT OF ANHYDROUS WAS RELEASED INTO THE AIR. SAFETY COMPLARS AND EXCESS FLOW VALVE DID NOT FUNCTION AS WOULD BE EXPECTED OF THEM. THERE WERE NO INJURES. RESIDENTS LOCATED WITHIN A MILE AND DOWNWARD WERE NOTIFIED. NO SIGNIFICANT AMOUNT OF NH3 SEEMED TO HAVE REACHED THE RESIDENTS. AREA WAS CHECKED FOR 1 1/2 HRS AFTER THE INCIDENT. MOST AMMONIA HAD DISSIPATED IN THE AREA BY THAT TIME.
